      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are.  Even if you separate them across the galaxy, measuring a property of one particle instantly tells you the corresponding property of the other.  The key difference from classical correlation is that this connection is *stronger* than anything classical physics allows; it's not just that they were pre-programmed, but their properties are truly correlated at the moment of measurement. This instantaneous link is what baffled even Einstein, who famously called it \"spooky action at a distance.\"",
      "source": "target",
