    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if there's no hidden instruction set or \"socks in a box\" rule, how do physicists actually prove that there isn't just some invisible, tiny force or something we haven't discovered yet acting as the middleman? it's hard to wrap my head around the idea that there's no actual \"thing\" connecting them.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To rule out those \"hidden variables\"—the invisible middleman forces—physicists rely on experimental tests, most famously those based on Bell's inequalities. These tests set limits on how strongly correlated two particles *can* be if they are governed by any local, classical hidden mechanism. If the experimental results consistently violate these limits, it proves that the correlations are too strong to be explained by any pre-existing local instructions. Essentially, the math of the correlations themselves acts as the proof against a simple, hidden connection.",
      "source": "target",
